<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900628-0018</DOCNO><DOCID>900628-0018.</DOCID><HL>   California Sues Keating,   Others Over Sale of Bonds</HL><DATE>06/28/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6</SO><CO>   AMC</CO><IN>SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)</IN><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- The state of California sued Charles H.Keating Jr., several officers and directors of AmericanContinental Corp. and the company's former accountant foralleged fraud in the sale of $250 million in now-worthlessbonds.   The complaint, filed in Orange County Superior Court,seeks restitution for bondholders and civil penalties thatcould range from $50 million to $100 million. The suit is thelatest in a barrage of litigation seeking &quot;deep pockets&quot; torepay investors and others in the collapse of Lincoln Savingsandamp; Loan Association, a subsidiary of American Continental.</LP><TEXT>   The defendants include Jack Atchison, a partner in theaccounting firm of Arthur Young andamp; Co. who later went on towork for American Continental. Arthur Young, which now doesbusiness as Ernst andamp; Young, also is named in the complaint. AnErnst andamp; Young spokesman said the company hadn't seen the suitand couldn't comment.   The subordinated debentures were sold through Lincoln'sbranches, and the suit alleges that the company specificallytargeted elderly investors for the bond sales. The governmentalleges that the thrift's collapse may cost taxpayers morethan $2 billion.   James Feder, an American Continental lawyer, called thesuit &quot;a waste of time and money&quot; and said the allegations ofa policy to sell the bonds to the elderly were not true.Lawyers for Mr. Atchison weren't immediately available tocomment.</TEXT></DOC>